<paragraph blockId="8.[227,1436,1929,2026]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Anseeuw, Puillandre, Utge &amp; Bouchet" authorityYear="2015" box="[227,589,1929,1955]" class="Gastropoda" family="Pleurotomariidae" genus="Perotrochus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Pleurotomariida" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="pseudogranulosus" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[227,589,1929,1955]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Perotrochus pseudogranulosus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[595,684,1929,1955]" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
most closely resembles 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Bouchet &amp; Metivier" authorityYear="1982" box="[965,1132,1929,1955]" class="Gastropoda" family="Pleurotomariidae" genus="Perotrochus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Pleurotomariida" pageId="8" pageNumber="9" phylum="Mollusca" rank="species" species="caledonicus">
<emphasis box="[965,1132,1929,1955]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">P. caledonicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1147,1215,1929,1955]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="12.[225,268,1934,1960]" captionTargetBox="[225,1434,302,1909]" captionTargetId="figure@12.[225,1434,302,1909]" captionTargetPageId="12" captionText="Fig. 7. A–F. Perotrochus caledonicus Bouchet &amp; Métivier, 1982. A–B. MNHN-IM-2000-1262, holotype (H = 31.2 mm). C–D. MNHN-IM-2007-36300 (H = 51.2 mm). E–F. MNHN-IM-2007-36301 (H = 47.5 mm). — G–L. Perotrochus deforgesi Métivier, 1990. G–H. MNHN-IM-2000-1391, holotype (H = 33.9 mm). I–J. MNHN-IM-2007-32062 (H = 33.7 mm). K–L. MNHN-IM-2007-32085 (H = 25.1 mm)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.3785281" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/3785281/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="9">Fig. 7</figureCitation>
) at first glance, but is distinguished by its more conical and higher shell, a more flattened basal disc profile and a more intense and regular checkerboard colour pattern and more lustrous shell surface. It differs from 
